    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nRunning `:checkhealth` in nvim on Windows 10 gave me a configuration error:\r\n\r\n`ERROR Locale does not support UTF-8. Unicode characters may not display correctly.\r\n 15   $LANG=nil $LC_ALL=nil $LC_CTYPE=nil\r\n 16   - ADVICE:\r\n 17     - If using tmux, try the -u option.\r\n 18     - Ensure that your terminal/shell/tmux/etc inherits the environment, or set $LANG explicitly.\r\n 19     - Configure your system locale.`\r\n \r\n I was able to get rid of it by setting the locale in my config:\r\n\r\n`vim.api.nvim_exec('language en_US', true)`\r\n\r\nI wondered if it is planned to support setting the language natively via Lua with e.g. `vim.opt.language = en_US` because it seemed strange that such a basic thing is not supported yet.\r\nOr is the locale setting error supposed to be differently on Windows?\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nAdding `vim.opt.language = en_US` to init.lua would resolve the Locale configuration error.",
